# Cypress + Next.js Streaming

When a route has a `loading.tsx` (Suspense boundary), the skeleton HTML arrives before the server component content streams in. Cypress `cy.visit()` resolves on the `load` event, which fires during the skeleton — **not** after streaming completes.

## After navigating to a page, always wait for streamed content

Assert on an element that only exists in the **real** page, not the skeleton, before interacting.

```typescript
// ❌ BAD — URL changes while skeleton is still showing
cy.visit(`/app/applications/${id}`)
cy.contains('button', /acciones/i).click()

// ❌ BAD — URL updates before content streams in
cy.findTableRow('25,000').find('a').click()
cy.url().should('match', /\/app\/applications\/\d+/)
cy.contains('button', /acciones/i).click()

// ✅ GOOD — guard on content that proves streaming finished
cy.visit(`/app/applications/${id}`)
cy.contains(applicant.name).should('be.visible')
cy.contains('button', /acciones/i).click()
```

## Prefer positive assertions over negative ones for async actions

After a server action (form submit, dialog confirm), assert the **next expected state** rather than the absence of the previous state.

```typescript
// ❌ BAD — races against animation + server action latency
cy.contains('button', /confirmar/i).click()
cy.get('[role="dialog"]').should('not.exist')

// ✅ GOOD — retries until the new state appears
cy.contains('button', /confirmar/i).click()
cy.get('[data-status="rejected"]').should('be.visible')
```
